tweet: 6/ In solving number 2, AI is used to remove the noise in the point cloud model. When creating point clouds many objects in the city create noise that reduces the accuracy of alignment when stitching point clouds together. We use AI to identify and remove this. https://t.co/3avFwxCpou

tweet:
5/ Alignment accuracy and speed are mainly determined by the following factors:
1) Accuracy of GPS coordinates acquired by smartphone
2) Amount of noise of moving objects such as people and cars
3) Percentage of repeating structures in the acquired point cloud
user bio: Symmetry Dimensions develops a #DigitalTwin platform and XR tools for professionals in urban planning, architecture, and construction.

tweet:
4/ Workflow:
- Obtain the reference point cloud with a laser surveying instrument
- Get point clouds for individual locations from a mobile
- Update the 3D map of the urban space by automatically and accurately superimposing the point cloud acquired by the mobile on the reference

tweet: I find this claim pretty plausible. Tech market equilibria in 2022 tend to make duopolies, so I can imagine exactly N=2 such "megabrains." The Q is whether those moats are defensible. Not certain; I could see it going either way. A higher-N future also seems possible.
user bio: Author of The Alignment Problem, Algorithms to Live By (with Tom Griffiths), and The Most Human Human. Visiting Scholar at UC Berkeley.

tweet: (3) Andrej suggests that "the whole setting of training a neural network from scratch [...] is quickly becoming outdated due to finetuning," & that in 2055 we’ll all query one of some small number of "10,000,000X-sized neural net megabrain[s]" via prompt engineering / English.
user bio: Author of The Alignment Problem, Algorithms to Live By (with Tom Griffiths), and The Most Human Human. Visiting Scholar at UC Berkeley.

tweet: So, progress in language models may well come from increasing model size, but IMO dataset size is already hitting a wall. Will be interested to see what that looks like, whether it’s a problem or not, or if there are clever workarounds, in 2055.
user bio: Author of The Alignment Problem, Algorithms to Live By (with Tom Griffiths), and The Most Human Human. Visiting Scholar at UC Berkeley.

tweet: He suggests in 2055, "datasets [of] today look like a joke. [They] are somewhere around 10,000,000X larger." For vision, I can see that. But for language models, no! In 2022 we are already using almost *all of the written text there is* in the world!
user bio: Author of The Alignment Problem, Algorithms to Live By (with Tom Griffiths), and The Most Human Human. Visiting Scholar at UC Berkeley.

tweet: @BasilHalperin The same is true for "if I cooperate, he cooperates" - you just need to understand it as a higher-level intervention, over not just your decision but rather the common factor between your decision and his decision (namely, your shared decision algorithm).
user bio: Figuring out how the future works @OpenAI.

tweet: @BasilHalperin Your atom-level response is too strong because it rules out normal counterfactuals too. When I say "if I'd never joined twitter, then X" the antecedent may be physically impossible - since I did join twitter! But we can understand it as a claim about a higher-level intervention.
user bio: Figuring out how the future works @OpenAI.

tweet:
@BasilHalperin The intuition here is that even *after* you are cloned, you are able to (correctly) reason "if I cooperate he will cooperate, and if I don't he won't".

This reasoning doesn't make sense under classical counterfactuals. Since it works, we need a better notion of counterfactuals.

@muninJLM מחיר ומהירות הבנייה הם לרוב לא הבוטלנקים לדיור חדש, בייחוד לא באזורי הביקוש. צריך קרקע יקרה, צריך אישורים.
אפשר לבנות הרבה דיור זול כבר היום אם מוכנים לוותר על תקן חניה ועל שלושה כיווני אוויר. כבר היום אפשר לעשות את זה באזורים עם תחבצ טוב

@raz__mor @isrPiccolo @criticalmassil @itay_timor @MeravMichaeli @naftalibennett @yairlapid אמא שלי בת 62, נוסעת באופניים ולא מתכוונת להפסיק. ככה עוד הרבה אנשים. חוץ מה שלא צריך שכולם יסעו באופניים, אלה שצריכים לנסוע ברכב או בתחבורה ציבורית יהנו מהירידה בעומס בכבישים. ברור שצריך גם מטרו, אבל הרבה מהנסיעות במרכז הן קצרות ויכולות להתבצע באופניים.

@Averroes811 @ReemSherman לא בטוח שהטכנולוגיה הזאת תהיה פיזיבילית לעולם. כרגע אנחנו משקיעים בערך פי 10 אנרגיה מהאנרגיה השימושית שזה מייצר, וזה במתקן שעלה מיליונים. עד שזה יתחרה בביקוע או במתחדשות, אם בכלל, בקלות יכול לקחת עוד 50-100 שנה
@ItsAaronKlar @allonsigler אפילו זה לא יעזור, כי הוא צריך לחצות כביש מהיר באמצע
@michalglass @TheClimatist יותר מדי צל? מישהו שכח כמה חם פה בקיץ?

@RanShuhami מספר פעמים יצא לי לפנות גם למפעילות וגם למשרד התחבורה בטופס האינטרנטי. בערך כל התשובות  שקיבלתי מהמפעילות היו "תפנה למשרד התחבורה" או "הנהג פעל לפי הוראות משרד התחבורה"
ממשרד התחבורה תמיד המליצו לי לקחת אוטובוסים אחרים שבכלל לא עצרו בתחנה שעוזרת לי.
@yuval_weinreb @ReemSherman תוכנה היא לב העניין? הנהיגה האוטונומית של טסלה הרחק מאחורי המתחרות. יש מערכת infotainment מעולה אבל זה לא קשור לזה שהרכב חשמלי, שם האתגר  הוא בעיקר הנדסי ולוגיסטי.

tweet:
11/ Penalties/ Slashing

- when slashed, an active validator is ejected from the current set and loses some ETH
- the amount of ETH they can lose is variable, depending on a few factors (see image) https://t.co/OoQKA2UQEg
user bio:

creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
10/ Penalties/ Slashing/ anti-correlation

- the same anti-correlation incentives also apply here! when many validators are getting slashed, the penalty is higher
- STAKE INDEPENDENTLY W/ A MINORITY CLIENT
- IF YOU CAN'T, ASK YOUR STAKING PROVIDER TO USE A MINORITY CLIENT
user bio:
ECOSYSTEM PERSON @ EF → bridging between stakeholder groups
creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
9/ Penalties/ Slashing conditions

- when a proposer signs two different beacon blocks for the same slot
- when an attester signs an attestation that “surrounds” another one
- when an attester signs two different attestations having the same target
user bio:
ECOSYSTEM PERSON @ EF → bridging between stakeholder groups
creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
8/ Penalties/ Slashing

- this is usually what people think of w/ PoS penalties
- slashing _only_ happens when the system views a val. action as an attack: even if due to bugs or configuration issues
- not all PoS systems have slashing!
- see "5. Whistleblower" above
user bio:
ECOSYSTEM PERSON @ EF → bridging between stakeholder groups
creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
7/ Penalties/ Inactivity Leak/ anti-correlation

- correlated downtime of a majority client can cause an accelerated leak to kick in, your val. being penalized more
- similarly: if everyone used AWS & it had an extended outage, or worse, censorship from the company
user bio:
ECOSYSTEM PERSON @ EF → bridging between stakeholder groups
creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
6/ Penalties/ Inactivity Leak

- in normal network conditions, a val. loses approx. what they wld have earned in the same period if they were online
- however, losses can be much higher if there are many vals. offline: the system views it as an attack on chain finalization
user bio:
ECOSYSTEM PERSON @ EF → bridging between stakeholder groups
creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
5/ Rewards/ Whistleblowing

- when a slashable offense occurs (see "9. Slashing Conditions" below), the system still needs to record it to reduce the offender’s ETH balance
- any val. which includes this whistleblowing message in a block gets ~.0625 ETH
user bio:
ECOSYSTEM PERSON @ EF → bridging between stakeholder groups
creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
4/ Rewards/ Block Proposing

- every slot, a val. is selected to propose a block
- val. then bundles attestations and proposes it as a block
- more attestations included = higher ETH reward
- currently around ~.025 ETH
user bio:
ECOSYSTEM PERSON @ EF → bridging between stakeholder groups
creating the Protocol Guild → @statefulworks

tweet:
3/ Rewards/ Attestations

- each slot, a set of validators vote on what they see as the head of the chain
- ETH reward scales by how quickly & accurately the validator can get out this information. correct and faster = higher (see image)
- currently ~.00002 ETH per slot https://t.co/CevH8Or58P
